where the jury has misconducted itself, such as where a stranger was permitted in the jury room (Goby v Wetherill [1915] 2 KB 654), or a juror is a member of a corporation which is a party (Atkins v Fulham Borough Council (1915) 31 TLR 564), or where the jury shows partiality against a party before hearing his case: Allum v Boultbee (1854) 23 LJ Ex 208. Evidence may not, however, be led as to what occurred in the jury room: David Syme & Co Ltd v Swinburne (1909) 10 CLR 43; [1910] VLR 539 ; Shoukatallie v R [1962] AC 81; [1961] 3 All ER 996 ; cf Ellis v Deheer [1922] 2 KB 113 and Prothonotary v Jackson [1976] 2 NSWLR 457 and Attorney-General v New Statesman and Nation Publishing Co Ltd [1981] QB 1; [1980] 1 All ER 644 : see also 
